---
title: "ggseg3d walkthrough"
---

```{r}
#| label: wt-setup
#| include: false
knitr::opts_chunk$set(
  eval = TRUE,
  fig.width = 7,
  fig.height = 5,
  fig.path = "img/"
)
library(ggseg3d)
library(dplyr)
```

ggseg3d renders interactive 3D brain atlases using WebGL.
Version 2.0 rebuilt the package on Three.js, replacing the previous Plotly backend.
This brings faster rendering, a pipe-friendly API, and unified brain atlases that work with both ggseg and ggseg3d.

## Basic usage

Call `ggseg3d()` without arguments to plot the Desikan-Killiany atlas:

```{r}
#| label: wt-basic
ggseg3d(hemisphere = "left") |>
  pan_camera("left lateral")
```

The widget is interactive:
- **Rotate**: click and drag
- **Zoom**: scroll wheel
- **Pan**: right-click and drag

Hover over regions to see their names.

## Camera positions

Use `pan_camera()` to set the viewing angle:

```{r}
#| label: wt-camera-preset
#| eval: false
ggseg3d() |>
  pan_camera("left lateral")
```

```{r}
#| label: wt-snap-camera-preset
#| include: false
ggseg3d() |>
  pan_camera("left lateral") |>
  snapshot_brain("img/wt-camera-preset.png")
```

```{r}
#| label: wt-fig-camera-preset
#| echo: false
#| fig.cap: "Left lateral view of the Desikan-Killiany atlas."
knitr::include_graphics("img/wt-camera-preset.png")
```

Available presets:
- `left lateral`, `right lateral`
- `left medial`, `right medial`
- `left superior`, `right superior`
- `left inferior`, `right inferior`
- `left anterior`, `right anterior`
- `left posterior`, `right posterior`

For custom positions, pass a list:

```{r}
#| label: wt-camera-custom
#| eval: false
ggseg3d() |>
  pan_camera(list(eye = list(x = -200, y = 100, z = 100)))
```

## Plotting your data

Provide data with a `region` or `label` column matching the atlas.
Map it to `colour_by` for the fill and optionally `text_by` for hover info:

```{r}
#| label: wt-plot-data
#| eval: false
some_data <- tibble(
  region = c("precentral", "postcentral", "insula", "superior parietal"),
  p = c(0.01, 0.04, 0.2, 0.5)
)

ggseg3d(.data = some_data, atlas = dk(), colour_by = "p", text_by = "p") |>
  pan_camera("right lateral")
```

```{r}
#| label: wt-snap-plot-data
#| include: false
some_data <- tibble(
  region = c("precentral", "postcentral", "insula", "superior parietal"),
  p = c(0.01, 0.04, 0.2, 0.5)
)

ggseg3d(.data = some_data, atlas = dk(), colour_by = "p", text_by = "p") |>
  pan_camera("right lateral") |>
  snapshot_brain("img/wt-plot-data.png")
```

```{r}
#| label: wt-fig-plot-data
#| echo: false
#| fig.cap: "Brain regions coloured by p-value."
knitr::include_graphics("img/wt-plot-data.png")
```

## Custom colour palettes

Pass colours as a vector:

```{r}
#| label: wt-palette-vector
#| eval: false
ggseg3d(
  .data = some_data,
  atlas = dk(),
  colour_by = "p",
  palette = c("forestgreen", "white", "firebrick")
)
```

Or use a named vector to control breakpoints:

```{r}
#| label: wt-palette-named
#| eval: false
ggseg3d(
  .data = some_data,
  atlas = dk(),
  colour_by = "p",
  text_by = "p",
  palette = c("forestgreen" = 0, "white" = .05, "firebrick" = 1)
)
```

```{r}
#| label: wt-snap-palette-named
#| include: false
some_data <- tibble(
  region = c("precentral", "postcentral", "insula", "superior parietal"),
  p = c(0.01, 0.04, 0.2, 0.5)
)

ggseg3d(
  .data = some_data,
  atlas = dk(),
  colour_by = "p",
  text_by = "p",
  palette = c("forestgreen" = 0, "white" = .05, "firebrick" = 1)
) |>
  snapshot_brain("img/wt-palette-named.png")
```

```{r}
#| label: wt-fig-palette-named
#| echo: false
#| fig.cap: "Custom green-white-red palette with breakpoints at 0, 0.05, and 1."
knitr::include_graphics("img/wt-palette-named.png")
```

This lets the colour bar extend beyond your data range.

## Background colour

Change the background with `set_background()`:

```{r}
#| label: wt-background
#| eval: false
ggseg3d() |>
  set_background("black")
```

```{r}
#| label: wt-snap-background
#| include: false
ggseg3d() |>
  set_background("black") |>
  snapshot_brain("img/wt-background.png")
```

```{r}
#| label: wt-fig-background
#| echo: false
#| fig.cap: "Brain atlas with a black background."
knitr::include_graphics("img/wt-background.png")
```

## Region edges

> **Experimental.** Edge rendering works in the htmlwidget viewer but rgl
> support (`ggsegray`) is still unreliable across platforms. Expect rough
> edges (pun intended).

Add outlines around regions with `set_edges()`:

```{r}
#| label: wt-edges
#| eval: false
ggseg3d(hemisphere = "left") |>
  set_edges("black", width = 10) |>
  pan_camera("left lateral")
```

```{r}
#| label: wt-snap-edges
#| include: false
ggseg3d(hemisphere = "left") |>
  set_edges("black", width = 10) |>
  pan_camera("left lateral") |>
  snapshot_brain("img/wt-edges.png")
```

```{r}
#| label: wt-fig-edges
#| echo: false
#| fig.cap: "Left hemisphere with black region boundary edges."
knitr::include_graphics("img/wt-edges.png")
```

### Edge boundaries with edge_by

By default, edges appear between regions with different colours.
Use `edge_by` to define boundaries based on a different column:

```{r}
#| label: wt-edge-by
#| eval: false
lobe_data <- tibble(
  region = c("precentral", "postcentral", "insula", "superior parietal"),
  p = c(0.2, 0.4, 0.3, 0.5),
  lobe = c("frontal", "parietal", "insula", "parietal")
)

ggseg3d(.data = lobe_data, atlas = dk(), colour_by = "p", edge_by = "lobe") |>
  set_edges("white", width = 1) |>
  set_background("black")
```

```{r}
#| label: wt-snap-edge-by
#| include: false
lobe_data <- tibble(
  region = c("precentral", "postcentral", "insula", "superior parietal"),
  p = c(0.2, 0.4, 0.3, 0.5),
  lobe = c("frontal", "parietal", "insula", "parietal")
)

ggseg3d(.data = lobe_data, atlas = dk(), colour_by = "p", edge_by = "lobe") |>
  set_edges("white", width = 1) |>
  set_background("black") |>
  snapshot_brain("img/wt-edge-by.png")
```

```{r}
#| label: wt-fig-edge-by
#| echo: false
#| fig.cap: "Lobe-based edge boundaries on a dark background."
knitr::include_graphics("img/wt-edge-by.png")
```

Regions in the same lobe won't have edges between them.

## Subcortical structures

For subcortical atlases, reduce opacity of uncoloured regions and add a glass brain:

```{r}
#| label: wt-subcortical
subcort_data <- tibble(
  region = c("Thalamus", "Caudate", "Hippocampus"),
  p = c(0.2, 0.5, 0.8)
)

ggseg3d(
  .data = subcort_data,
  atlas = aseg(),
  colour_by = "p",
  text_by = "p",
  na_alpha = .5
) |>
  add_glassbrain()
```

The glass brain adds a translucent cortical surface for anatomical context.

## White matter tracts

The `tracula` atlas renders white matter pathways as tube meshes:

```{r}
#| label: wt-tracula-basic
ggseg3d(atlas = tracula()) |>
  add_glassbrain(opacity = 0.1)
```

### Mapping data to tracts

Map data the same way as cortical or subcortical atlases. The `region` column
matches tract names:

```{r}
#| label: wt-tracula-data
tract_data <- tibble(
  region = c("arcuate fasciculus", "corticospinal tract",
             "cingulum bundle", "uncinate fasciculus"),
  fa = c(0.45, 0.55, 0.40, 0.35)
)

ggseg3d(
  .data = tract_data,
  atlas = tracula(),
  colour_by = "fa",
  text_by = "fa"
) |>
  add_glassbrain(opacity = 0.1)
```

### Orientation colouring

Set `tract_color = "orientation"` for direction-based RGB colouring --- red for
left-right, green for anterior-posterior, blue for superior-inferior:

```{r}
#| label: wt-tracula-orientation
ggseg3d(atlas = tracula(), tract_color = "orientation") |>
  add_glassbrain(opacity = 0.1) |>
  set_background("black")
```

### Tube appearance

Control tube geometry with `tube_radius` and `tube_segments`:

```{r}
#| label: wt-tracula-tube
#| eval: false
ggseg3d(atlas = tracula(), tube_radius = 4, tube_segments = 16) |>
  add_glassbrain(opacity = 0.1)
```

Larger `tube_radius` makes tracts thicker. More `tube_segments` makes them
smoother but increases rendering time.

## Saving images

Use `snapshot_brain()` to save static images:

```{r}
#| label: wt-snapshot
#| eval: false
ggseg3d() |>
  pan_camera("left lateral") |>
  snapshot_brain("brain_lateral.png")
```

This requires Chrome or Chromium.

### Publication-quality settings

For journal figures, increase resolution:

```{r}
#| label: wt-snapshot-hires
#| eval: false
ggseg3d(.data = some_data, atlas = dk(), colour_by = "p") |>
  pan_camera("left lateral") |>
  set_background("white") |>
  snapshot_brain(
    "figure1_brain.png",
    width = 1200,
    height = 1000,
    zoom = 3,
    delay = 2
  )
```

- **width/height**: Output dimensions in pixels
- **zoom**: Resolution multiplier (2-3 for print)
- **delay**: Seconds to wait for rendering

### Multi-panel figures

Save individual views and combine them:

```{r}
#| label: wt-multi-panel
#| eval: false
library(magick)

base_plot <- ggseg3d(.data = some_data, atlas = dk(), colour_by = "p") |>
  set_background("white")

base_plot |>
  pan_camera("left lateral") |>
  snapshot_brain("left_lat.png")
base_plot |>
  pan_camera("left medial") |>
  snapshot_brain("left_med.png")
base_plot |>
  pan_camera("right lateral") |>
  snapshot_brain("right_lat.png")
base_plot |>
  pan_camera("right medial") |>
  snapshot_brain("right_med.png")

panels <- image_read(c(
  "left_lat.png",
  "left_med.png",
  "right_lat.png",
  "right_med.png"
))
combined <- image_montage(panels, geometry = "600x500", tile = "2x2")
image_write(combined, "figure1_all_views.png")
```

## Legend control

Hide the legend:

```{r}
#| label: wt-legend
#| eval: false
ggseg3d() |>
  set_legend(FALSE)
```

## Widget dimensions

Set explicit width and height:

```{r}
#| label: wt-dimensions
#| eval: false
ggseg3d() |>
  set_dimensions(width = 800, height = 600)
```

## Flat shading

Disable lighting for exact colour reproduction:

```{r}
#| label: wt-flat-shading
#| eval: false
ggseg3d() |>
  set_flat_shading()
```

```{r}
#| label: wt-snap-flat-shading
#| include: false
ggseg3d(hemisphere = "left") |>
  set_flat_shading() |>
  pan_camera("left lateral") |>
  snapshot_brain("img/wt-flat-shading.png")
```

```{r}
#| label: wt-fig-flat-shading
#| echo: false
#| fig.cap: "Flat shading disables lighting for exact colour reproduction."
knitr::include_graphics("img/wt-flat-shading.png")
```

This is useful when creating atlases or when you need colours to match exactly.

## Orthographic projection

Switch from perspective to orthographic projection:

```{r}
#| label: wt-orthographic
#| eval: false
ggseg3d() |>
  set_orthographic()
```

```{r}
#| label: wt-snap-orthographic
#| include: false
ggseg3d(hemisphere = "left") |>
  set_orthographic() |>
  pan_camera("left lateral") |>
  snapshot_brain("img/wt-orthographic.png")
```

```{r}
#| label: wt-fig-orthographic
#| echo: false
#| fig.cap: "Orthographic projection --- regions appear the same size regardless of distance."
knitr::include_graphics("img/wt-orthographic.png")
```

## Same atlas for 2D and 3D

The `ggseg_atlas` class works with both ggseg and ggseg3d.
Use the same atlas object for both:

```{r}
#| label: wt-same-atlas
#| eval: false
library(ggseg)

plot(dk())

ggseg3d(atlas = dk())
```
